{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774458186,"nonce":"/zQTjrfti9/AUHhKvmq7iFQbdgg=","title":"Part 2 analysis: single-unit stimulation and functional characterization","message":"Umbrella: 0af472c (Part 2)\n\n**Motivation:** Characterize the functional role of individual units by stimulating them and measuring behavioral consequences. This goes beyond tuning curves (Part 1) to establish causal unit-to-behavior mappings, and tests whether these mappings change with SISU context.\n\n**Approach:** Apply constant input to individual network units (via `NetworkConstantInput` intervenor) at varying amplitudes, crossed with SISU levels and plant perturbation amplitudes. Measure response variables: max deviation, max speed, and angle of deviation after stimulation. Compute regression of response variables against SISU/perturbation regressors. Also: steady-state input Jacobian decomposed by RNN input channel (SISU, position, velocity) to characterize per-unit input sensitivity. PCA visualization of hidden state trajectories under unit stimulation.\n\n**Status:** Module exists at `src/rlrmp/modules/analysis/part2/unit_perts.py`. Most complex analysis module. Many components are implemented but commented out (Jacobian regression, feedback gain analysis, unit preference during stimulation, hidden state PC plots). Active analyses: stimulus response profiles and response distribution violins.\n\n**References:** Perturbation/stimulation paradigm; related to Jazayeri \u0026 Afraz (2017) for causal perturbation of neural circuits.","files":null}]}